> We're remixing Chinese sweet 'n' sour into something a little bit different. Rather than
> relying on a sugary sauce, this recipe uses the natural sweetness of pineapple,
> the savory notes of soy, and a splash of vinegar tang to transform it into something
> fresher and more flavorful.

Wash and dry all produce. Bring @water{1 3/4%cups}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and a
pinch of @salt{} to a boil in a #medium pot{}. Core and seed @red bell pepper{1}(seeded and
cut into 1-inch squares). Trim @scallions{4}(trimmed and cut into 1-inch pieces). Peel @ginger{1%thumb}(peeled and minced or grated). Drain @pineapple{12%ounce}(drained,
reserving juice), reserving juice. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/2%ounce}.

Once stock is boiling, add @jasmine rice{1%cup} to #pot{}. Give it a stir, reduce to a
simmer, and cover. Cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Remove from heat and keep
covered.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat (use a #nonstick pan{} if you have one). Add ginger and cook until fragrant, about
~{1%minute}. Add @ground pork{20%ounce}, breaking up meat into pieces. Season generously
with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, tossing occasionally, until browned and just cooked
through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Remove from #pan{} and set aside.

Heat another large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in same pan over medium-high
heat. Add bell pepper, scallions, and @snow peas{4%ounce}. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Cook, tossing, until vegetables are tender but still have a little bite,
about ~{5%minutes}. Remove from pan and set aside.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together @water{1/2%cup}, reserved pineapple juice,
@soy sauce{4%tablespoon}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @brown sugar{1%tablespoon},
@cornstarch{2%tablespoon}, and @white wine vinegar{1%tablespoon}. Add to same pan and
bring to a boil, then lower heat and let simmer until slightly thickened,
~{3-5%minutes}.

Return pork and veggies to pan with sauce and toss to combine. Add pineapple and half
the cilantro and stir until warmed through. Fluff rice with a #fork{}, then season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Divide between plates and top with stir-fry. Sprinkle with
remaining cilantro.